But wait - the guard checks `bake.stateSnapshot.status === "running"`. If the pipeline starts, the status remains whatever it was before (probably "idle" from the previous state or from resetState()). If `runPipeline()` doesn't set it to "running", then the guard would never prevent concurrent runs.

Actually, this IS a problem. Let me re-read...

Looking at `bake.ts`:

```ts
runPipeline(): Promise<void> {
