So the old version also didn't have a running-state guard. But the old version was `await`ed, so only one pipeline could run at a time by virtue of being synchronous. The new fire-and-forget version removes the `await`, so now it's possible to call bake-start multiple times.

The guard is supposed to prevent this, but since `runPipeline()` never sets status to "running", the guard is ineffective.

Hmm, but actually - runPipeline calls `runBakePipeline` which creates a parentMachine that starts in "idle" state and transitions to "running" when START is sent. But `runBakePipeline` returns `{ passed, results }` only when the machine reaches "done" or "failed". The `Bake.state.status` is only set after that. So during execution, `Bake.state.status` never reflects "running".

This is a **real bug** - the guard doesn't work because `state.status` is never set to "running" before/during pipeline execution. Two concurrent calls to `bake-start` could both pass the guard and both start running the pipeline.

However, looking at the old code - the old `await bake.runPipeline()` blocked, so you couldn't have concurrent calls anyway. The old loader overlay was shown during the pipeline run, preventing the user from doing other things (or at least providing visual feedback). The new code makes the pipeline fire-and-forget but doesn't set state.status properly.

Actually, I need to check - does `runBakePipeline` (the XState machine) itself prevent concurrent runs? No - each call to `runBakePipeline` creates a new actor. So yes, concurrent calls would both try to process phases.

